    "question_id" : 3009745,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Perhaps a contrived \"real world\" example would help.</p>\n\n<p>At my place of work we have rubbish bins that come in different flavours. All bins contain rubbish, but some bins are specialist and do not take all types of rubbish. So we have <code>Bin&lt;CupRubbish&gt;</code> and <code>Bin&lt;RecylcableRubbish&gt;</code>. The type system needs to make sure I can't put my <code>HalfEatenSandwichRubbish</code> into either of these types, but it can go into a general rubbish bin <code>Bin&lt;Rubbish&gt;</code>. If I wanted to talk about a <code>Bin</code> of <code>Rubbish</code> which may be specialised so I can't put in incompatible rubbish, then that would be <code>Bin&lt;? extends Rubbish&gt;</code>.</p>\n\n<p>(Note: <code>? extends</code> does not mean read-only. For instance, I can with proper precautions take out a piece of rubbish from a bin of unknown speciality and later put it back in a different place.)</p>\n\n<p>Not sure how much that helps. <em>Pointer-to-pointer in presence of polymorphism isn't entirely obvious.</em></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
